google_play_reviews.content: Generally, works as expected in identifying the local wifi hotspots and providing the basic mac, channel info and graphs.      That said, interface can be awkward. Eg. The 2.4Ghz graph puts the entire range (ch1-13) on one screen, but the 5Ghz graph splits it into 3 screens you must toggle among. Not useful.    Eg. The access point list has no icon to allow quick sort by name, mac, channel. It also lists the exact frequency used, but that's a slow way to tell if an access point is running on 2.4 or 5 ghz. The icon should be different to quickly indicate this as well as the fastest connection type (eg. B, G, AC...).     No intelligent labeling of the graph, so if 5 access points use the same cancel, all the names overwrite each other. You're forced to click the channel to display each one by one. Slow. Much easier if all the names simply were displayed Above  all the channel dB curves, in the order of displayed frequency strength.
It a great for Wi-Fi setup and troubleshooting. It's open source and that's great. The UI is not that great, but it's functional.
Quality stuff, and open source to boot.
